To improve the water quality of the effluent discharged to the receiving stream, the HARWWTF utilizes sulfur dioxide gas, another regulated substance, to de-chlorinate its effluent through a process called sulfonation.  The sulfonator is similar to the chlorinator and injects sulfur dioxide gas into wastewater to remove excess chlorine.  A maximum of four (4) one-ton containers may be on-site simultaneously; therefore, the maximum intended inventory for planning purposes is 8,000 pounds. 

Atmospheric dispersion modeling was performed using the RMP*Comp program distributed by the Chemical Emergency Preparedness and Prevention Office of the United States Environmental Protection Agency (USEPA).  This model determines the distance traveled by chlorine and sulfur dioxide released until concentrations decrease to the toxic endpoint of 0.0087 milligrams per Liter (mg/L) and 0.0078 mg/L, respectively, as selected by USEPA.  Both toxic endpoint concentrations in air represent the American Industrial Hygiene Association (AIHA) Emergency Response Planning Guideline (ERPG)-2, defined as the maximum airborne concentration below which it is believed that nearly all individuals could be exposed for up to 1 hour without experiencing or developing irreversible or other serious health effects or symptoms which could impair an individual's ability to take protective action.  This amount corresponds to 3.0 parts per million by volume.   

The HARWWTF Accidental Release Prevention Program is based upon the following elements:
1.	Routine training for the operators;
2.	Preventative maintenance program for equipment;
3.	Use of industry-standard process and safety equipment;
4.	Use of effective standard operating procedures, written with the participation of the operators;
